entry.title: Presubmit script for WebDatabase changes.
entry.content:
Adds a presubmit script that verifies that that whenever the current DB

version changes, the current tested version is updated correctly. The

script furthermore checks that a new golden file of the right database

version is added.



This can prevent mistakes and necessary clean-ups in the future. E.g.:

- Golden files were incorrect updated (or not at all) in the past.

See crrev.com/c/4521341.

- Updating the current tested version was forgotten in the past. This

caused a non-passing tested to be added, which was never run. This

in turn caused problems for the next person updating the database.

See crrev.com/c/3941628 and the eventual fix in crrev.com/c/3957538.



Script in action (see screenshots for the commands used for testing):

- Tested version not updated:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/3d9irLdVMcrsuqY

- Golden file not added:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/9tNZx9kM7sNnFHm

- Golden file naively copied without updating the version:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/D2HaVckVMYRZWAt

(In this case another presubmit error is triggered, since the

build file isn't updated)

- Unrelated change (no warning expected):

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/4P6nXeQ5LJ3isoC

entry.title: Shared Storage: Add PermissionsPolicy method for Opt-In feature
entry.content:
Shared Storage is adding an opt-in feature `sharedStorageWritable`

for `fetch()` similar to `browsingTopics`. Hence it needs to be able

to check the `kSharedStorage` PermissionsPolicy on an opt-in basis

for subresource requests, similarly to how Browsing Topics

accomplishes this.



At the call sites in the renderer where the checks are to be performed, however, we won't have access to a `network::ResourceRequest` to use

the existing method `IsFeatureEnabledForSubresourceRequest()`. Moreover,

`blink::ResourceRequest` is in blink/renderer/platform and so can't

be used here. Thus we add a new method to perform the needed check.



We also add `mojom::PermissionsPolicyFeature::kSharedStorage` to

the checks for existing opt-in features in the currently existing

method `IsFeatureEnabledForSubresourceRequest()`, in order to ensure

that this method is kept up-to-date with the full list of opt-in features.



This is part of a project to add support to writing to shared storage

from response headers. See

https://github.com/WICG/shared-storage/pull/70 for more information

and https://crrev.com/c/4444068 for a working prototype for `fetch()`.

entry.title: [iOS] Remove BrowserLauncher
entry.content:
BrowserLauncher's sole remaining purpose is to provide a BrowserState to

AppState for saving cookies when backgrounding. AppState already has

a BrowserState (via its public MainBrowserState property), so this seems

clearly redundant.



This is actually a functional change, however, although it appears to be

a bug fix. AppState used the "current browser"'s browser state to get

the URLRequestContext to clear cookies. The "current browser" might be

either regular or incognito, so presumably in some circumstances this

is saving the wrong cookies.



In addition, AppState was not actually using the MainAppDelegate param

it was initialized with. This reduces the dependencies for AppState to

just StartupInformation.



Beyond this, a lot of the cleanup in this CL is adding an explicit

include for browser_provider_interface.h for the many many files that

relied on getting it transitively from browser_launcher.h.



All of the tests that create or fake AppState are updated to use the

new init, removing many instances of mocked BrowserLaunchers and

MainApplicationDelegates that were, or are now, totally spurious.



(Some unit tests had C++ style updates as well).

entry.title: [EnumSet] Refactor constructor usages
entry.content:
TL;DR: EnumSet variadic template ctor is being replaced with ctor

accepting std::initializer_list. Some usages are not compatible and this

CL updates them.



Implicit EnumValue->EnumSet conversions and direct calls of variadic

template constructor (e.g. EnumSet(value1,...)) don't work with

initializer_list ctor. This CL replaces them with:

1. [Only variables initializations] EnumSet set = {value1, ...};

2. [Only inside macro invocations] EnumSet({value1, ...})

3. Implicit construction from initializer_list (note that this is a

special case of implicit conversion, intentionally supported in STL

and by clang-tidy warnings):

foo(value1) -> foo({value1});

foo(EnumSet(value1, ...)) -> foo({value1, ...});

4. EnumSet(value1, ...) -> EnumSet{value1, ...};



Note that 3 and 4 are mostly the same, in most places I made a choice

that resembles pre-existing code closer (exceptions are mostly usages of

Sync EnumSets).



Motivation:

EnumSet variadic template constructor is defective in a sense that it

allows code like this to compile:

using ModelTypeSet = EnumSet;

void foo(ModelTypeSet set);

foo(ModelType()); // Typo, intended to pass empty ModelTypeSet.



The problem is that constructor is not explicit. Simply making it

explicit will disallow nice STL-like usage:

class C {

ModelTypeSet set = {HISTORY, BOOKMARKS};

};



STL and other containers under base/containers avoid this problem by

using std::initializer_list, this refactoring does the same for EnumSet.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: Deflake ParallelDownloadTest.MiddleSliceDelayedError
entry.content:
The test often fails with timeout.

The test attempts to achieve following order of events:

1. File is being downloaded in three slices, meaining three parallel

requests.

2. Third request completes successfully first.

3. Second request receives headers (not a strong requirement, may

predate 2.).

4. First request completes its own slice and slice that belongs to the

second request.

5. Second request receives full response, but fails to write the data.

6. [Verification] Download is completed successfully, since first

request didn't fail to write and there is a special logic that allows

preceding request complete the work of their successors (but not

otherwise).



The problem is how test waits for 4. and how write failure for 5. is

implemented: second write at offset that belongs to second request

fails. Wait for 4. wasn't done in a correct way: it simply waits for

response being sent from the server, while test needs to wait until it

is processed by the client including file write. So, sometimes first

request fails instead of second and that causes timeout.



This CL makes waiting condition more accurate: until whole file is

written. To ensure that test still makes sense, there is a check that

download is not marked as completed until second request is processed.

entry.title: [iOS] Inject the frame id for each ContentWebFrame
entry.content:
In ios/web/content, frame ids are chosen on the browser side. The

approach of choosing ids on the JavaScript side, as happens in

WKWebView-based ios/web, cannot be used since messages do not arrive

with any identifier for the RenderFrame that sent them. Instead,

the browser chooses the id for each RenderFrameHost and then needs

to ensure that JavaScript uses that id.



This CL handles this by injecting a replacement for the existing

__gCrWeb.message.getFrameId() function that returns the chosen id.



This CL also moves the logic for telling observers that a WebFrame

became available from DidFinishNavigation to DOMContentLoaded, since

DidFinishNavigation is too early -- this happens when the navigation

is committed, which is early enough that JavaScript executed at this

point will race with document start scripts, and sometimes run before

these scripts (at which point __gCrWeb has not yet been set up).

entry.title: Hue component should be powerless for fully transparent colors
entry.content:
A new day, a new time to delete

color-computed-color-mix-function-expected.txt



The spec could have been read somewhat ambiguously in the past. Hue

angles are not premultiplied and therefore are affected more when

mixed with very nearly transparent colors. This produces the somewhat

unexpected effect that mixing with a fully transparent rgb color

will modify the hue angle, but nothing else in the color.



Discussion here clarified that when converting a fully transparent

rectangular color to a polar color space, the resulting hue angle

should be "none":

entry.title: Reland "[wayland] Cancel dnd when drag target or dragged window destroyed"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0d9b005cd03fcea1466c8ee5e7f600690a8e380e



See diff against patchset 1 for changes to the original CL.



The original CL was reverted due to flaky failures of the following

test case

WaylandWindowDragControllerTest.

HandleDraggedWindowDestructionAfterMoveLoop



When `move_loop_handler->RunMoveLoop({})` is called it is expected

the server generates a wl_data_device.data_offer and

wl_data_device.enter event. The `drag_target_window_` is set during

a drag when the enter event is received.



The issue was that sometimes ``move_loop_handler->RunMoveLoop({})``

would return before the client had received the offer and enter

events, and sometimes not.



If there is no enter received by the client, the target window is

not set - and deleting the target window will not cancel the drag.

When the events arrive later in this case the offer / enter events

are correctly no-oped as the window does not exist.



The inconsistency of delivered events for the test made it impossible

to test without flakiness. This CL added a call to `wl::SyncDisplay()` and updated expectations for what occurs when the target window is

destroyed.



Original change's description:

> [wayland] Cancel dnd when drag target or dragged window destroyed

>

> This CL updates the WaylandWindowDragController to cancel the dnd

> session client-side when either of the drag target window or the

> dragged window are destroyed.

>

> The dnd session is not cancelled when either the pointer grab or

> origin window are destroyed as this occurrence is already supported

> and defined by the dnd code.

>

> The client terminates the dnd session by calling OnDataSourceFinish()

> which resets the wl_data_source and performs some client-side

> cleanup. The spec indicates that the destruction of the data source

> can be performed to cancel the dnd session.

>

> To handle any possible events sent by the server, but not yet

> received by the client after the dnd session has been cancelled, the

> client will no-op any further dnd events after this has occurred.

>

entry.title: FSA: Exclusively lock swap files
entry.content:
Currently, creating a writable file stream takes a shared lock on the

file, with the idea that multiple writable streams may be associated

with the same file. However, writable streams are expected to be

siloed; creating multiple writers should create a swap file per writer



However, until this CL, the swap file itself was completely unlocked.

Since the swap file lives alongside the file (in the same directory),

sites with access to the parent directory could acquire a file handle

to the swap file directly. This leads to unexpected behavior, such as

the ability to create a writable stream from a swap file.



Ideally this would be tested in WPTs, but swap files are

implementation-defined and it's unclear whether it should even be

possible to acquire a handle to one in the first place.

would allow us to effectively call URL#setURLStreamHandlerFactory

entry.title: Remove rationalization from FieldTypeFromAutocompleteAttributeValue
entry.content:
Before this CL, FieldTypeFromAutocompleteAttributeValue took the string

value of the autocomplete and the max-length attribute of a form control

to return a HtmlFieldType. It contained heuristics to use the max-length

attribute to generate rationalized HtmlFieldTypes. For example, an

was mapped to an

The implementation came with two drawbacks:

1) The max-length had to be carried through many function calls.

2) The heuristic cannot be smarter. E.g. an
autocomplete="cc-exp-year" placeholder="YYYY"> could not be mapped to

HtmlFieldType::kCreditCardExp4DigitYear.



By splitting the rationalization from the parsing, we can improve this.



The new rationalization is implemented in https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4493243 but more will follow.

entry.title: Refactoring the race handling to be more comprehensive
entry.content:
This is a refactoring CL to make the race condition handling more

simpler and comprehensive.



As the discussion in the previous CL pointed[1], it's very unlikely in

theory but there could be the case that neither RaceNetworkRequest nor

the fetch handler commits the response. Also, the previous CL introduces

additional properties which manage the race condition between

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient and the owner loader class, which are

complicated.



This CL removes below properties from the class:

- `request_completed_` in RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient

- `is_fetch_handler_response_fallback_` in

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient

- `fetch_response_from_` in ServiceWorkerResourceLoader



Instead, `commit_responsibility_` will be added to

ServiceWorkerResourceLoader. It is the property replacing

`fetch_response_from_`, and literally telling who should commit the

response in the end, RaceNetworkRequest or the fetch handler. When the

fallback or the network error happens, the client can tell the other

side to commit the response. The race can just simply tell who is

responsible to commit the final response, it doesn't have to know the

state of the other side, like the fallback result of the fetch handler,

the network error in RaceNetworkRequest etc.



[1]

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4514795/comment/21231808_966a5777/

entry.title: Enable DPD feature flag on android-arm64-rel
entry.content:
The Dangling pointer detector is controlled by a binary flag and a

runtime flag:



1. The binary flag enable_dangling_raw_ptr_checks:

This flag controls the size of PartitionAlloc refcount, it

increases from 32 bits to 64 bits. It changes the behavior of

PartitionAlloc when a raw_ptr becomes dangling, calling

PartitionAlloc’s embedder.

This flag requires BackupRefPtr and PartitionAlloc to be enabled to

be effective.

2. The runtime flag PartitionAllocDanglingPtr:

This flag controls the behavior when a dangling pointer is

detected.

By default the dangling pointer is ignored.



This CL activates the dangling pointer feature flag on android-arm64-rel

. This using the binary flag

"enable_dangling_raw_ptr_feature_flags_for_bots" to change the default.



Additional dangling pointer detection documentation available in:
